# arvo-spectral — backlog

> **Type-surface reminder**: new entries use `arvo::USize` /
> `Bool` / `UFixed<N, 0, S>` instead of `usize` / `bool` / `u*`;
> `notko::Maybe` / `Outcome` instead of `Option` / `Result`. See
> `rules/type-surface.md`.

## Mask256 partition outputs

`spectral_bisection` / `k_way_partition` ship with `Mask64` and
`[USize; N]` outputs respectively — supports N ≤ 64. `Mask256`-backed
siblings would support N ≤ 256. Spectral methods are typically small-N
(per polka-dots research N ≤ 32 is common), so this is a widening for
atypical workloads, not a default need.

## Non-dense matrix formats

Current signatures take `&[[W; N]; N]` dense. If a consumer has a
sparse weighted graph via `arvo-sparse::Csr`, they densify at the
boundary. A direct sparse path would save memory on very sparse
matrices but adds an API variant; promote when a consumer's cache
profile actually benefits.

## Other decompositions

SVD, QR, LU, Cholesky are all plausible additions if a consumer
surfaces a concrete need. Keep spectral partitioning (Laplacian →
Fiedler → bisection) as the sole shipping surface this round.

## Non-symmetric matrices

Current `fiedler_vector` assumes the weighted adjacency is symmetric
(Laplacian derivation requires it). For directed graph spectral
analysis we would need a different construction (Markov / normalized
Laplacian on the underlying undirected graph). Not shipping.
